No. Changing an image reference can't create duplicate env vars — the image repository/tag and the container's `env` list are separate fields in the pod spec. Swapping `docker.io/...` for your ECR URI only changes where the image is pulled from; it adds nothing to the environment. So if you edit only the image fields, that really is all that changes — env, config, and secrets stay exactly as they are.

Duplicate env var names come from a different thing entirely: setting the same variable in two places. The usual cause is putting something in `additionalEnv` that the chart already generates from its structured values — e.g., hand-writing a `DATABASE_URL` while `postgres.host`/`auth` are also filled in, so the chart emits its own copy. That's unrelated to the registry switch, and since the ECR work doesn't need any `additionalEnv`, it introduces no new duplicate risk at all.

If a duplicate ever does slip in, Kubernetes won't error — it allows it, and the last entry in the list wins — but it's worth avoiding, since which value actually applies isn't obvious.

To confirm before applying, render the chart and scan the env block:

```bash
helm template langfuse langfuse/langfuse -f values.yaml > rendered.yaml
```

Open the web/worker deployment's `env:` section — the chart's own vars plus anything in your `additionalEnv` are the only sources, so any repeated `- name:` is something set twice.